#extra-chapter(none, "The Classical Literature Club president")[
  Our club name, "Classical Literature Club", was not entirely accurate.

  Japanese people consider classical literature to be works published prior to
  the Meiji era, before our culture was immensely influenced by Western works
  due to the modernization process.

  For Westerners, the term refers to works dating from even earlier, like in
  ancient civilizations, say Greece or the Roman Empire, dating for as long as
  thousands of years. Despite most of them being lost to the flow of time, it
  was still a marvelous fact that people in the modern world could still enjoy
  the handful remaining works as much as the ancient ones.

  Yet, in our club, we read post-World-War works like it was a normal Tuesday.
  Sometimes, we would go and fetch a translation of Shakespeare's plays, even
  though they were classified as post-classic. Not just literature, we also read
  technical documents, history reports, lyrics from an old folklore song, or
  anything that was composed of words and sentences that originated from at
  least 20 years ago.

  So, what does "classical" mean for our club, you may ask.

  It's actually very simple.

  Anything that takes place _a while ago_, say, before the 2000s, would qualify
  as a "classical work" in our eyes. Heck, I would even slip in something in the
  2010s if it's really good. However, there is a very important condition.

  Apart from that loosely-defined timestamp, in order to be classified as a
  "classic" work by the "Classical Literature Club" was that, the work must have
  no, ABSOLUTE ZERO inspirations, references or connections to the otaku culture
  prevalent in modern Japan.

  Hence, the following are counterexamples to our definition of a "classical"
  work:

  A light novel with its title longer than a high school essay.

  A fantasy novel parroting the same "banished from the hero's party" trope.

  A web manga that started with the ever-familiar scene of "I hereby declare my
  annulment of the engagement with you, the villainess".

  Honestly, no one on their right mind would qualify a manga as "classical
  literature", so I'm not even sure why I even listed that last example.

  But don't have any wrong idea. I don't hate otaku culture at all. Their
  community too. They can be weird at times, but I can tolerate it. I even had
  some light novels at home, too! But they are just not the "self-insert fantasy
  isekai overpowered MC" kind of light novels.
  //
  // Right, if you can't tell, I hate these tropes more than anything else. Just a
  // bunch of slop that for some reason sells like hot cakes.

  Anyway, the reason we have to ban all sorts of otaku media stems from the
  innate desire to protect ourselves.

  Long ago, we used to be the "Literature Club". Gosh, that name is so awkward to
  pronounce, as if eating ice cream cones without the ice cream itself. One
  beautiful day, a bunch of new kids (well, they are older than me now) decided
  to join. They looked good-natured and polite, so club president at the time
  let them in the club without any opposition.

  And that exact moment was when he opened the Pandora Box.

  The next day, and another group of juniors showed up. He let them in, like the
  previous bunch. In the following day, the same thing happened, yet he was too
  busy to really suspect what could be going on.

  And in the weekly club gathering, our club, for the first time, had more than
  100 members participating. Good thing, right?

  No.

  When the club president asked everyone, "What did you all read this week?",
  those new kids took out their so-called novels with soft-core porn right on
  the cover, proudly announcing to the club that they had been reading
  "Self-insert garbage with zero literary value"! Even worse, when that club
  president told the teachers, they said that there was no problem, and that was
  "how modern literature really is".

  I may sound like a boomer, but I'm not. Really!

  Okay, you may argue that, "It's their own choice to read whatever they want".
  No, they were ruining the essence of the club. If they wanted an otaku club,
  they should go make one instead of raiding another. And no, arguing whether
  the "best girl" be the big-boob girl or the long hair one is not a
  "constructive debate".

  And they even had the nerve to ask around about girls their age's three sizes
  "as reference for writing"? What the hell could they be thinking back then,
  even!

  _But the teachers supported them?_ No, they were just avoiding their
  responsibilities. Imagine finishing your lectures and _still_ having to settle
  up pointless drama of high schoolers, no one would do that kind of stuff
  unpaid. Teachers back then was less motivated than they were now, y'know.

  After a while of back-and-forth, the club president finally reclaimed our
  club, this time with a huge prefix "CLASSICAL" in front of the old club name.
  And that was how we survived until today. As the current president of the
  club, I have no intentions of removing it, too.

  Anyway, that was kind of sidetracked, I admit. Back to the present, there were
  only the two of us in the clubroom. Two of us, yes. Sitting right next to me
  was Tsukishima Ako, the vice president of the Classical Literature Club, as
  well as my lifelong sidekick, if I have to say.

  Currently, I'm reading a history book on the socio-political situation of the
  15#super[th] century Europe as reference for my next work, a psychological
  drama taking place in that era. I have a general idea for the protagonist, but
  I'm still debating on how I will do the worldbuilding.

  Honestly, as interesting as it all is, the text I'm reading does resemble
  something akind to a lullaby. I can fall asleep any time now...

  "Haizz- Why is 15#super[th] century so complicated... Who is the good guy, who
  is the bad guy? Why does every source seem to contradict each other..."

  "I mean that part was explicitly abridged in the history textbook. It's your
  fault for wanting to write a story with that messy background."
  The girl sitting next to me commented in an annoying tone.

  "But it's interesting right? So many different sources not agreeing on the
  most basic facts. It's like I'm reading a mystery novel, y'know."

  Though, I haven't read any mystery novel properly, so maybe my analogy was not
  an appropriate one.

  "Right, Dr. Sherlocks Koto." The girl playfully remarked.

  "Then, you are my assistant, Dr. Ako Watson."

  "Whatever."

  The girl returned to reading her thick novel. _Helicopter_, as I like to call
  it, was a pretty well-written one. As a romance story, it's pretty average, to
  say the least, but what really made it apart from other novels were the
  accurate portrayal of the split between the conservative Japanese who clung to
  traditional values and the reformists who doubted everything they were taught
  prior. Unlike other works written during that era, it did not align with one
  side and hurl insults to the other, but rather portraying the two groups as the
  inevitable consequence of a deeply broken post-war society.

  The girl abruptly closed her book. Just as I was intending to ask her what's
  up, she spoke up loudly,

  // our goat satou matsuzaka
  "I almost forgot. Satou-sensei asked me to do her a favor."

  "Photocopying test papers again?"

  "Not that. She wanted me to fetch her some books from the library."

  "Well, I'll go with you. I'm kind of bored with this historical reference,
  anyway."

  Honestly, it was not that boring. The opening was pretty well-written, but the
  writing quality seemed to decline as I continued reading. To the point that
  some paragraphs were outright contradicting the previous sections.

  _"It was as if someone tried to alter this historical record or something."_

  I sighed. The library still had some texts on 15#super[th] century Europe, so
  I might go and get those. I thought that a book this thick could be enough
  for my research, but it seemed that I was mistaken.

  "Let's go, then."

  I slipped my favorite bookmark between the pages I was reading and got to my
  feet. We slid the windows shut, in case something bad could happen, got out of
  the room and locked the door.

  The library, well calling it a library might make it sound too grandiose was
  just two unused interconnected classrooms in the floor above. There was not
  even a librarian there, only teachers and trusted students (like me and Ako)
  were allowed to enter. When our club members wanted to retrieve something, Ako
  or me usually had to tag along to open the door for them.

  Satou-sensei could go fetch the shared key to go to the library by herself,
  but as the procedure was quite annoying, she entrusted that task to us from
  time to time.

  On the way to the library, we met a familiar face. The girl with long black
  ponytails stood in the middle of the stairs, while looking at her smartphone
  with great anticipation. Her cheeks were burning red, as if someone just went
  and asked her out.

  Nevertheless, I could kind of guess what was happening.

  "Takamizawa-san! Don't just stand at the stairs, won't you?"

  // con chao me
  // W me kiet
  "Heh\-? Since when?" She shrieked. At least her cheeks were returning to the
  usual orange-pink color.

  "So, Koyuki-senpai asked you out, again?" Ako remarked with a playful tone,
  "Ah, If only I could fall in love, too!"

  "Was it that obvious?" The girl worriedly asked.

  "Kind of." I chuckled.

  "I mean he's asking you pretty politely here..." Ako pointed at the message on
  Takamizawa-san's smartphone. If she was flustered, she should really turn off
  the screen or something, how silly of her.

  "Wait! Don't just look at other's cell phones like that!" She followed my
  untold suggestion, promptly putting the phone into her bag, "Tsukishima-san!
  Can you act like a proper high school student, please?"

  "No, I'm not\~" Ako pulled out her tongue, "Have a nice date, Arisa-chan!"

  Her cheeks exploded at the sound of a "date". It was so cute that I almost
  chuckled. Then, I felt something like a deadly glare aimed at me. Phew, glad
  that I did not let out any noise.

  "Anyway, I'm going." The girl turned around, probably heading back to her
  place.

  However, I could not let it end here.

  "Takamizawa-san, are you serious about it?"

  I changed my voice. It was no longer the playful tone of a girl toying a
  lovesick friend of hers, but a more serious and mature one.

  "About what?"

  She changed her tone, too. She must have already known what I was talking
  about.

  "The club disbandment plans, I mean." I reconfirmed.

  "Yes, I am." She immediately replied.

  "But it would be too cruel for _her_, wouldn't it?"

  I slipped out my inner thoughts. Didn't mean to do that at all.

  "Cruel? She was the cruel one." Takamizawa-san turned around at me with a sour
  face, angrily remarking, "She was running for that role against me, yet she
  dropped out the moment she lost."

  "But..."

  I couldn't say it. More like I did not have the permission to.

  "Goodbye. You guys should be unscathed with your awards, so don't get
  involved with us."

  Takamizawa-san walked down the stairs, her figure lowered and lowered until we
  could not see her at all.

  "As stubborn as ever." Ako commented.

  "I mean Takamizawa-san has been like that ever since she enrolled here." I
  gave a faint smile, "I just wish they could make up someday..."

  "With how stupid Arisa-chan is, I don't think they could, honestly." Ako
  pouted.

  "Haha-, well, should we continue?"

  After a brief while of walking, we finally arrived at our destination. I
  opened the door with the key entrusted to me, then pull the door wide open.

  This is our sanctuary.

  Bookshelves of various kinds as far as the eyes can see.

  A dusted reading table that no one dared to sit at.

  It was like a time capsule, as if nothing had changed since the last time I
  was here.

  "So what was she asking for?"

  "Let me see..." Ako opened the notes app on her phone, "'A critic of Mejiro's
  Life', 'Young girls in the deep night', and er- 'Don't leave me alone, baby!
  volume 8'."

  "What a mood killer..." I remarked, "She finished volume 7 already?"

  "Seems so."

  Satou-sensei's library requests usually had these kinds of books. BL, if I'm
  not mistaken. She might not look like it, but she was a die-hard fujoshi.
  I think we were the only ones in this school knowing that side of her, which I
  don't know whether to feel proud about it or not.

  And before you ask "What is a BL novel doing in the school library", let me
  explain. Our library is basically a glorified garbage dump for books. Our
  school, apparently, bought unmarketable books from local bookstores with a low
  price, and those books were transported here.

  Even though these were supposed to be "unsellable" books, it was not as bad as
  you might think. In fact it was the reverse: books that sold like hot cakes
  were even worse than these, since they, well, were the light novels that I
  spent half of this chapter criticizing. Timeless classics, on the other hand,
  would be ignored by those tasteless modern readers, and ended up in the box of
  "shelf-warmers".

  Well, it was a good thing that we could read these books for basically free, I
  guess.

  As for the BL novel from earlier that I'd rather not say the title, it was
  a series published before BL was huge, so it was unsellable, too. There were
  also a couple of other series in the same boat in this huge catalog, too.

  I went to the history shelf to pick references for my 15#super[th] century
  Europe novel. Since the historical tome I fetched before was a pain to read, I
  think I should grab at least two titles. Okay, let's see...
  "15#super[th]-century: A Breakdown for the Modern Historians", "The luxurious
  // erm is that referencing that manga...
  life of Pia-sama", "Luna revolt: a chronological timeline". Hmm, these all
  sounded fascinating, so I might grab all of them.

  Once I finished choosing the books I was going to read, I met up with Ako, who
  had finished fetching the books that Satou-sensei requested. We got out of the
  room, then I locked the door.

  We went down the stairs. Even though Ako could go alone, I did not want to
  // giong may voi chi tam
  slip this chance of meeting Satou-sensei and at least saying hello to her, so
  I went with her instead of returning to the club room. Regardless, it was
  still a pain since the teachers' room is located on the first floor.

  After climbing four-floors-worth of stairs, we finally arrived at our next
  destination.

  The door was not as jammed as the library door, so a light slide could let us
  enter.

  // more describing????
  There, I saw no one but a female teacher with shoulder-length hair, typing
  something to her working tablet. Aside from her, all the other teachers seemed
  to have already gone home.

  "Satou-sensei, here is your delivery. The shipping fee is 10000 yen, thank
  you!"

  Ako's playful voice distracted the lone teacher from her work,

  "Ah- Tsukishima-san, and Miyano-san, too! Thanks for the work."

  I slightly bowed down to say hello to her. We gave her the _goods_, and no,
  there is no shipping fee, it was just a stupid joke from Ako.

  "I spent the whole night reading volume 7, can't wait to read the next one!"

  "That's why you read it that quick, huh?"

  "I mean, it was just that good that you could not even bring yourself to
  sleep!" Satou-sensei remarked, "You two are in the Literature club, so you
  know what I mean, right?"

  "I guess so, haha... There was a novel series that I spent the whole night
  reading too." I commented.

  "You two are really..." Ako sighed, "Sensei, did you even do today's lectures
  properly? Don't tell me that you fell asleep and let everyone do what they
  please?"

  "Hmmph, nothing that a cup of coffee cannot handle." She waved an empty can of
  coffee in front of us. Hey... There were like five other empty cans on her
  desk. Don't say that she drank all of that today?

  "Sensei, caffeine overdosing is a real threat..." I mumbled, yet in a serious
  voice.

  "I know, I know. It's just a special occasion, okay!" Sensei chuckled, "Ah,
  right, I forgot! Miyano-san, I haven't congratulate you for the scholarship,
  right?"

  "It's not that big of a deal, sensei..." I scratched my head, smiling
  helplessly at Satou-sensei's poor attempt of changing the topic.

  "No!" Sensei abruptly stood up, "Having my student being awarded that
  'special-grade extraordinary performance scholarship' has been my dream since
  I started teaching. I almost teared up when I saw you along with
  Takamizawa-san and Setoguchi-san, y'know..."

  "Me too, sensei! I bawled my eyes out when I saw her being awarded the
  certificate." Ako jumped into the conversation.

  "Why does it seem like you two are happier than I am..."

  We continued chatting for a while before it was late. Me and Ako went back to
  the club room to pick up our stuff (yay, more climbing stairs), before we
  parted way.

  All alone under this dusk sky, I began to recollect everything that happened
  for the past year.

  How Ako had been helping me with socializing.

  How Satou-sensei became the club's advisor after our selfish request.

  How I got that Best Novel Award at the fair, and being awarded the scholarship
  too.

  Since the day I became club president, I felt like my world had drastically
  changed. It was only thanks to the people who stayed by my side that I could
  have made such miracles come true.

  Now that I'm a second-year student at Misuzu, I will try my best to pay back
  everyone's kindness.

  Even if it cost me my own life.
]

